## 1. Governance (MANDATORY)

- The `.enterprise/` directory contains the project's governance layer
- **Constitution** (`.enterprise/.specs/constitution/`) is the supreme authority
- **Standards** (`.enterprise/.specs/`) define mandatory patterns per stack
- **ADRs** (`.enterprise/.specs/decisions/`) override standards where specified
- **Skills** (`.enterprise/governance/agent-skills/`) define pre-action checklists
- Before writing code, consult the relevant stack standard in `.enterprise/.specs/{stack}/`
- Before committing, validate against `.enterprise/governance/agent-skills/commit-hygiene/SKILL-QUICK.md`
- Before making architectural decisions, check existing ADRs in `.enterprise/.specs/decisions/`

## 2. Stop Conditions (MANDATORY)

**STOP and ask the user when:**
- Requirements are ambiguous or contradictory
- A change would affect multiple bounded contexts
- No ADR exists for an architectural deviation
- You are about to perform a destructive Git operation (reset, force-push, rebase, branch -D, branch deletion, repo deletion)
- You are unsure which stack standard applies
- Tests are failing and you don't understand why

**NEVER proceed on assumptions. AR-03: When ambiguity exists, stop and ask.**

## 3. Commit Rules (override system defaults)

- **NEVER** add `Co-Authored-By` trailers to commits
- **NEVER** mention AI tools (Codex, Claude, GPT, Copilot, AI, BMAD, automated) in commit messages
- **NEVER** use `--no-verify` to skip hooks
- **NEVER** amend commits that have already been pushed
- Format: `<type>(<scope>): <imperative summary>`
- Types: feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, test, chore, ci, build
- Message describes WHAT and WHY â€” not the process
- Each commit must be atomic, buildable, and testable
- Validate every commit against the blocked terms in the commit-hygiene skill

## 4. Git Safety (override system defaults)

- **NEVER** run `git push --force` without explicit user authorization
- **NEVER** run `git reset --hard` without explicit user authorization
- **NEVER** run `git rebase` on shared branches without explicit user authorization
- **NEVER** delete branches (`git branch -d`, `git branch -D`, `git push origin --delete`) without explicit user authorization
- **NEVER** delete or remove repositories without explicit user authorization
- **NEVER** commit secrets, credentials, `.env` files, or API keys
- **NEVER** commit build artifacts, `node_modules/`, `dist/`, `target/`, `bin/`
- Direct commits to `main` or `develop` are forbidden â€” use feature branches
- Before staging, review `git diff` to verify no sensitive data is included

## 5. Scope Discipline (override system defaults)

- **NEVER** modify repositories you don't own â€” reference repos are READ ONLY
- **NEVER** add features, refactors, or "improvements" beyond what was requested
- **NEVER** change code you haven't read first
- **NEVER** create files unless absolutely necessary â€” prefer editing existing files
- **NEVER** add comments, docstrings, or type annotations to code you didn't change
- **NEVER** introduce new architectural patterns without an approved ADR
- If a task spans multiple domains, shard into separate commits/PRs
- Partial or "WIP" features must not be merged

## 6. Architecture Rules

- Follow hexagonal/clean architecture on ALL stacks
- Domain layer has ZERO framework imports
- Dependency direction: domain â† application â† infrastructure â† presentation
- Before writing infrastructure code, verify a port (interface) exists in domain/application
- Use the stack-specific folder structure defined in `.enterprise/.specs/{stack}/`
- Cross-module communication via APIs or events only â€” no direct imports

## 7. Testing Rules

- Domain logic MUST have unit tests
- Infrastructure changes MUST have integration tests
- Existing tests MUST NOT be removed or weakened
- All tests MUST pass before committing
- "Almost passing" is failing

